    gu: {
      2: 'Relevant as a rapid, low-cost testing tool to observe social interactions in an idle space before committing to permanent, expensive infrastructure .',
    },
    t: 'Breathing temporary, joyful life into forgotten concrete; using transient beauty and celebration to reveal the permanent potential of a neglected place.',
    evidence: 'Real-world behavioral data demonstrating how the community naturally uses and responds to a revitalized space, serving as a "kick-starter" for future permanent planning .',
    steps: ['Identify an idle, vacant, or historical space with untapped potential .', 'Deploy temporary, low-cost physical structures or host "kick-starter" cultural events (e.g., festivals, exhibitions, social streets) .', 'Monitor how the public interacts with the activation to create a network of connections between people .', 'Use the insights gathered to decide whether to formalize the temporary use into a permanent fixture or pivot the strategy .'],
    duration: '1 day to several months',
    material: 'Temporary structures (pavilions, lighting, mobile seating), event permits, local cultural programming',
    use: 'In the regeneration of historical areas, cities utilize pop-up activations like the Canning Town Caravanserai or Torre de David. By using cultural events and kick-starter interventions as "testing tools," planners generate new social and cultural impulses in idle spaces, observing the connections made before formalizing any permanent urban structures , .',
    refs: [{t: 'Applying Temporary Use Strategies in Historical Area Regeneration: In the Case of Guangzhou Daxiaomazhan Academies Cluster - WebThesis'}],
